1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:26,500
 [Music]

2
00:00:26,500 --> 00:00:33,000
 I was trying to characterize, what is C++ particularly useful for, what did I actually build it for,

3
00:00:33,000 --> 00:00:43,000
 and what is its strength today after almost 30 years of evolution, and also where is the limits to where it is.

4
00:00:43,000 --> 00:00:55,000
 So, the way I see it is, there's a core domain for C++, and that's what you would call traditional systems programming,

5
00:00:55,000 --> 00:01:01,000
 but that's not the right term, because it's just a style of language and a style of programming.

6
00:01:01,000 --> 00:01:10,000
 So, I go a little bit further, I said, what is it that requires the kind of services that C++ has?

7
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:18,000
 What is the sum of all these applications I've been dealing with? Where did it work, and where was it essential?

8
00:01:18,000 --> 00:01:27,000
 And I came up with the phrase infrastructure, and I roughly define it as, if it breaks, somebody gets hurt or somebody gets ruined.

9
00:01:27,000 --> 00:01:37,000
 These are the kind of foundational things in our systems that must work for the system, for society to work.

10
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:43,000
 The question I'm trying to phrase is, what matters in those areas?

11
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:56,000
 And I've come up with some notions of compact data structures, very strongly typed interfaces for maintainability and for minimizing errors,

12
00:01:56,000 --> 00:02:08,000
 a heavier emphasis on algorithms or random code, because we need reliability, we need the stuff to be comprehensible, analyzable,

13
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:18,000
 we want to make sure that it's actually correct. And so, the paper I was writing comes from that kind of thinking.

14
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:29,000
 What is the right style, and what are the supports for that style we need for infrastructure software, for software that must be dependable?

15
00:02:29,000 --> 00:02:43,000
 I don't get real examples, sort of the keys of some of the modern operating systems, the basics of our phone system, the brakes in my car.

16
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:52,000
 How do we make that dependable? How do we make sure that space probes don't get the logical equivalent of a blue screen of death

17
00:02:52,000 --> 00:03:00,000
 halfway to Mars, where we can't send a repairman? How do we make sure that they actually go into the right orbits?

18
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:11,000
 JPL lost a probe off Mars because two groups had communicated nicely, they thought.

19
00:03:11,000 --> 00:03:18,000
 But in fact, one of them spoke imperial measures, and the other one spoke the SI system, the MKS system.

20
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:30,000
 And the result was a misnavigation that sent more than $500 million worth of equipment into the wrong orbit.

21
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:39,000
 Not a good idea. It was the work of 200 good engineers, lifetime's work, down the drain.

22
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:48,000
 And that could have been avoided by ever so slight improvement in the interfaces between the parts of that program.

23
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:58,000
 So things like that I'm interested in. So there's a core area where I think the facilities for C++, they're not perfect,

24
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:03,000
 the kind of things I would like, the kind of things I work on are essential.

25
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:13,000
 And then there's a huge gray area where you have choices, they can help in my opinion, but they're not essential.

26
00:04:13,000 --> 00:04:22,000
 Then you have areas where it probably is unsuitable to apply that kind of stringency technique.

27
00:04:22,000 --> 00:04:30,000
 I want to essentially get 100% reliability if I'm putting up a small application for my own use,

28
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:36,000
 or if somebody is trying to push out a little cute web app.

29
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:43,000
 They don't need that kind of reliability, and maybe what I'm talking about in terms of programming is not for them.

30
00:04:43,000 --> 00:04:49,000
 But I think the really important thing here is to realize that there are different techniques,

31
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:54,000
 different languages that apply to different areas, and we have to recognize this.

32
00:04:54,000 --> 00:05:02,000
 We can't have a single language for everybody, a single technique of using that language for everybody.

33
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:11,000
 We can't have a single tool chain or a single kind of system, and from there we can go a little bit further.

34
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:19,000
 We probably don't need the same kind of training for education for everybody.

35
00:05:19,000 --> 00:05:26,000
 The engineer, software developer, or whatever that is building infrastructure,

36
00:05:26,000 --> 00:05:34,000
 say the mechanism that automatically updates the software on a cell phone,

37
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:42,000
 has to have a different education, different knowledge, different training from the one that makes a little game.

38
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:55,000
 Because the one can actually destroy a whole day or a whole week for millions of people by a little slip.

39
00:05:55,000 --> 00:06:01,000
 Maybe even somebody gets hurt if the 911 calls don't get through, bad things happen.

40
00:06:01,000 --> 00:06:05,000
 And it's not just the software that runs on it, it's the update software.

41
00:06:05,000 --> 00:06:14,000
 It's anything in the chain of safety critical issues that has to be dealt with.

42
00:06:14,000 --> 00:06:20,000
 But somebody doing that has to think differently from somebody who writes a little application,

43
00:06:20,000 --> 00:06:26,000
 maybe to make a couple of bugs quickly.

44
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:29,000
 There's nothing wrong with that, but they have to think different.

45
00:06:29,000 --> 00:06:37,000
 As a matter of fact, if you apply this very strange engineering-oriented thinking to little commercial apps,

46
00:06:37,000 --> 00:06:42,000
 you'll probably be a year late to market, and it'll be irrelevant.

47
00:06:42,000 --> 00:06:47,000
 On the other hand, if you took the attitude of first to market is the only thing that happens,

48
00:06:47,000 --> 00:06:54,000
 and apply them to the steering wheel of my car, no, that's not a good idea.

49
00:06:54,000 --> 00:07:03,000
 Most people have to think different, and the way you get people to think differently is to give them different educations.

50
00:07:03,000 --> 00:07:07,000
 We don't have an anti-standard programmer, and we shouldn't have.

51
00:07:07,000 --> 00:07:10,000
 If it was, we should have several.

52
00:07:10,000 --> 00:07:18,000
 And I think the field has to, in some sense, clean up its act before somebody else comes in and tries to clean it up for us.

53
00:07:18,000 --> 00:07:24,000
 You can sort of make your own constants and have seconds after the constants.

54
00:07:24,000 --> 00:07:31,000
 Is that a feature that you added at some intermediate stage, or is that simple sort of operator overloading?

55
00:07:31,000 --> 00:07:40,000
 We were observing that we were getting a whole zoo of little suffixes out of the various fundamental types.

56
00:07:40,000 --> 00:07:48,000
 The U suffix is for unsigned, and L is for long, I think, and I can't remember them all anymore, and we thought, you know,

57
00:07:48,000 --> 00:07:53,000
 you can do anything in C++, but you can't make your own literals.

58
00:07:53,000 --> 00:08:02,000
 And then I'd observed separately that there was techniques that were effective,

59
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:07,000
 except that people would not use them because the notation was too ugly.

60
00:08:07,000 --> 00:08:12,000
 The Unix example is one of those.

61
00:08:12,000 --> 00:08:17,000
 You've been able to do everything in the Unix example I showed.

62
00:08:17,000 --> 00:08:21,000
 Not quite as elegant, but you can do everything I showed for the last ten years.

63
00:08:21,000 --> 00:08:23,000
 Libraries have been available.

64
00:08:23,000 --> 00:08:29,000
 There was a nice one from Fermilabs, back to Nice Places and Nice People again.

65
00:08:29,000 --> 00:08:34,000
 But it wasn't used as much as it should because the users didn't believe in the notation.

66
00:08:34,000 --> 00:08:36,000
 They didn't like it.

67
00:08:36,000 --> 00:08:42,000
 And so we were looking at how can you basically clean up people's source code?

68
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:48,000
 How can we make code look the way it would look in an ideal language?

69
00:08:48,000 --> 00:08:52,000
 How can we make code look much as it does in the textbooks?

70
00:08:52,000 --> 00:09:02,000
 So the Unix example is simply a way of getting your code to look the way equations look in your physics textbook.

71
00:09:02,000 --> 00:09:06,000
 We know how to avoid that Mars climate orbital problem.

72
00:09:06,000 --> 00:09:10,000
 Everybody had been taught it in physics in high school.

73
00:09:10,000 --> 00:09:15,000
 First, make sure your units match, then do the detailed calculation.

74
00:09:15,000 --> 00:09:17,000
 So why didn't people do it?

75
00:09:17,000 --> 00:09:20,000
 It was too cumbersome and it was too ugly when they did it.

76
00:09:20,000 --> 00:09:24,000
 Or too costly if they used runtime techniques.

77
00:09:24,000 --> 00:09:30,000
 So I, together with friends, we thought this problem was worth addressing.

78
00:09:30,000 --> 00:09:35,000
 We tried to figure out what solutions we had, went through several evolutions.

79
00:09:35,000 --> 00:09:41,000
 I think the last finishing touches was done by David.

80
00:09:41,000 --> 00:09:43,000
 And it's now standard.

81
00:09:43,000 --> 00:09:48,000
 This is one of the features that is not shipping widely today.

82
00:09:48,000 --> 00:09:54,000
 But wait a year and that example will probably run on your computer too.

83
00:09:54,000 --> 00:10:02,000
 Are there other kind of examples where you've let people from within a class create their own literals beyond sort of suffixes?

84
00:10:02,000 --> 00:10:12,000
 When I started out with C++, I provided constructors which allows you to construct objects of a certain type from arguments.

85
00:10:12,000 --> 00:10:14,000
 And that has been very effective.

86
00:10:14,000 --> 00:10:21,000
 And people have used constructors as if they were literals.

87
00:10:21,000 --> 00:10:23,000
 But they weren't.

88
00:10:23,000 --> 00:10:25,000
 That's a runtime cost.

89
00:10:25,000 --> 00:10:36,000
 So the first thing we did with C++ OX, C++ 11, was we introduced constant expressions as a more fundamental unit.

90
00:10:36,000 --> 00:10:41,000
 This was work between me and my colleague Gabriel Das Reis.

91
00:10:41,000 --> 00:10:46,000
 And we have constexpr functions that can be evaluated at compile time.

92
00:10:46,000 --> 00:10:52,000
 And we have constexpr types so that you can use type rich programming at compile time.

93
00:10:52,000 --> 00:10:59,000
 This is very important in sort of the high-performance computing and in the embedded systems world.

94
00:10:59,000 --> 00:11:01,000
 That was what we did to address that.

95
00:11:01,000 --> 00:11:12,000
 Constant expression evaluation is much more general, much easier to use, and yes, more pretty in C++ 11 than earlier versions.

96
00:11:12,000 --> 00:11:16,000
 So that just strengthens what the direction had gone before.

97
00:11:16,000 --> 00:11:27,000
 So you could write complex 1, 2 to make a complex number in C++ in 1984.

98
00:11:27,000 --> 00:11:35,000
 Today you can write the same thing and have the complex number created at compile time.

99
00:11:35,000 --> 00:11:37,000
 And therefore, say, put in ROM.

100
00:11:37,000 --> 00:11:44,000
 I don't know why you'd want a complex number on ROM, but you might want a point which is the same thing, point of 1, 2.

101
00:11:44,000 --> 00:11:48,000
 Now, you still have to write point or complex.

102
00:11:48,000 --> 00:11:58,000
 And the other thread of thinking in C++ works was to generalize and make safer the initialization.

103
00:11:58,000 --> 00:12:06,000
 And so it happens that if you know the type you need, like you have a function returning a complex number,

104
00:12:06,000 --> 00:12:13,000
 you can simply write open curly 1, 2, and it says, oh, 1, 2 is supposed to make you a complex number.

105
00:12:13,000 --> 00:12:17,000
 And it will make a complex number and return it.

106
00:12:17,000 --> 00:12:22,000
 And if you happen to be at compile time, you'll do that at compile time.

107
00:12:22,000 --> 00:12:27,000
 So things work together. You get better notation. You get better performance.

108
00:12:27,000 --> 00:12:34,000
 And anything you can do at compile time works even better in a concurrent system because you can't get a race condition on a constant.

109
00:12:34,000 --> 00:12:39,000
 If it's been calculated before the program starts, you can't get the threading problems.

110
00:12:39,000 --> 00:12:45,000
 So open curly means find a constructor for the thing that I'm about to put this in.

111
00:12:45,000 --> 00:12:47,000
 It looks at where the destination is.

112
00:12:47,000 --> 00:12:53,000
 And it says, is there a two parameter constructor or a three parameter constructor or whatever?

113
00:12:53,000 --> 00:12:57,000
 Or if it's just a struct, it will take the first element and put in the first element.

114
00:12:57,000 --> 00:12:59,000
 It does it for a struct as well?

115
00:12:59,000 --> 00:13:00,000
 Oh, yeah.

116
00:13:00,000 --> 00:13:04,000
 See, I haven't played in C++ in a while. That's a great idea.

117
00:13:04,000 --> 00:13:14,000
 It refers to this as uniform initialization. It will initialize if it can.

118
00:13:14,000 --> 00:13:18,000
 And if there's any ambiguity, it of course finds the ambiguity.

119
00:13:18,000 --> 00:13:29,000
 If you're in a context where, like you're calling a function, and the target could be a point or a complex number, it's a tough luck.

120
00:13:29,000 --> 00:13:31,000
 Tell me. Or tell me.

121
00:13:31,000 --> 00:13:35,000
 The error checking has actually been improved.

122
00:13:35,000 --> 00:13:43,000
 C++11 is slightly better at finding bugs than C++98 was.

123
00:13:43,000 --> 00:13:54,000
 I come from the school of philosophy that says that the compiler is your best friend when you generate code, when you build programs.

124
00:13:54,000 --> 00:14:00,000
 And to make it your best friend, you actually have to have more types.

125
00:14:00,000 --> 00:14:05,000
 If everything is an integer, well, what can the type system help you there?

126
00:14:05,000 --> 00:14:14,000
 No, it can't. If everything is a floating point number, it can't tell you whether it's imperial or OSI units, and you'll get bugs.

127
00:14:14,000 --> 00:14:21,000
 So you need type rich interfaces, and for that you need to be able to build cheap types, basically, and flexible types.

128
00:14:21,000 --> 00:14:22,000
 And convenient.

129
00:14:22,000 --> 00:14:33,000
 Types that's easy to use, simple. And so we worked from complex of 1,0, 1,2, or something like that.

130
00:14:33,000 --> 00:14:39,000
 So curly is 1,2, and type is optional. It's only needed when it's needed.

131
00:14:39,000 --> 00:14:59,000
 And then finally, we can now write, if we wanted to, 1+2i. Define i as the unit for the imaginary parts, and you get complex arithmetic without ever saying complex.

132
00:14:59,000 --> 00:15:03,000
 It's down in the definition of the i-surfix.

133
00:15:09,000 --> 00:15:23,000
 [Music]

